│ ### 1. Understanding the Issue                               │
│                                                              │
│ The `early-cse` pass is asserting in `combineIRFlags` when   │
│ processing a function with two calls to the commutative      │
│ intrinsic `@llvm.smin.i32`. The two calls have swapped       │
│ arguments. One call site has the `strictfp` attribute, while │
│ the other does not. The pass correctly identifies the two    │
│ calls as computationally equivalent due to the intrinsic's   │
│ commutativity. However, it fails when attempting to merge    │
│ the attributes of the two call sites.                        │
│                                                              │
│ ### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log                                 │
│                                                              │
│ The `opt` debug log shows that `early-cse` is attempting to  │
│ common subexpression eliminate (CSE) `%call2` with `%call`:  │
│                                                              │
│ ```                                                          │
│ EarlyCSE CSE:   %call2 = call i32 @llvm.smin.i32(i32 %arg1,  │
│ i32 %arg)  to:   %call = call i32 @llvm.smin.i32(i32 %arg,   │
│ i32 %arg1) #1                                                │
│ ```                                                          │
│                                                              │
│ `%call` has the `strictfp` attribute, while `%call2` does    │
│ not. The assertion failure occurs in `combineIRFlags`, which │
│ is called just before replacing `%call2` with `%call`. The   │
│ assertion `Success && "Failed to intersect attributes..."`   │
│ indicates that `tryIntersectAttributes` returned `false`.    │
│                                                              │
│ ### 3. Root Cause Analysis                                   │
│                                                              │
│ The root cause lies in the interaction between how           │
│ `early-cse` determines instruction equality and how it       │
│ merges call site attributes.                                 │
│                                                              │
│ 1.  **Equality Check**: `early-cse` uses                     │
│ `SimpleValue::isIdenticalTo` to check if two instructions    │
│ are CSE candidates. For commutative instructions, this       │
│ function canonicalizes the operand order before comparison.  │
│ In our case, `isIdenticalTo` correctly reports that `%call`  │
│ and `%call2` are identical because `@llvm.smin.i32` is       │
│ commutative. However, this check *does not* consider call    │
│ site attributes like `strictfp`.                             │
│                                                              │
│ 2.  **Attribute Merging**: After identifying the             │
│ instructions as identical, `early-cse` calls                 │
│ `combineIRFlags`, which in turn calls                        │
│ `CallBase::tryIntersectAttributes`. This function attempts   │
│ to merge the attributes of the two call sites. The           │
│ `strictfp` attribute is an `EnumAttribute` with a value of   │
│ `StrictFP`. The logic in `AttributeSet::intersect` for       │
│ `EnumAttribute`s requires that if an attribute exists on one │
│ set, it must also exist on the other set with the same value │
│ for the intersection to be successful.                       │
│                                                              │
│ 3.  **The Conflict**: In this scenario, `%call` has          │
│ `strictfp` and `%call2` does not. `tryIntersectAttributes`   │
│ is called on `%call` to intersect with `%call2`'s            │
│ attributes. The `strictfp` attribute from `%call` is not     │
│ present in `%call2`'s attribute set. This leads to           │
│ `AttributeSet::intersect` returning `false`, which           │
│ propagates up to `tryIntersectAttributes`, causing the       │
│ assertion failure in `combineIRFlags`.                       │
│                                                              │
│ The core problem is that the "identical" check is            │
│ disconnected from the attribute merging logic. The former    │
│ ignores attributes that the latter considers significant,    │
│ leading to an incorrect assumption that attributes can       │
│ always be successfully merged for "identical" calls.         │
│                                                              │
│ ### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                │
│                                                              │
│ The fix is to make the equality check in `early-cse` aware   │
│ of call site attributes that cannot be safely merged.        │
│ Specifically, `SimpleValue::isIdenticalTo` should be         │
│ modified to check for incompatible attributes like           │
│ `strictfp` when comparing `CallBase` instructions.           │
│                                                              │
│ **File**: `llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/EarlyCSE.cpp`          │
│                                                              │
│ **Edit Point**:                                              │
│                                                              │
│ ```cpp                                                       │
│ // llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/EarlyCSE.cpp                   │
│                                                              │
│ // ... inside SimpleValue::isIdenticalTo(const Instruction   │
│ *I)                                                          │
│     // We can CSE calls to the same pure function with the   │
│ same arguments.                                              │
│     if (const auto *CB = dyn_cast<CallBase>(Inst)) {         │
│       if (const auto *OtherCB = dyn_cast<CallBase>(I)) {     │
│         // The called values must be the same.               │
│         if (CB->getCalledOperand() !=                        │
│ OtherCB->getCalledOperand())                                 │
│           return false;                                      │
│         // The argument lists must be the same.              │
│         if (CB->arg_size() != OtherCB->arg_size())           │
│           return false;                                      │
│                                                              │
│         // If the calls have different strictfp attributes,  │
│ they are not identical.                                      │
│         if (CB->isStrictFP() != OtherCB->isStrictFP())       │
│           return false;                                      │
│                                                              │
│         // We can CSE calls if they are readonly and not     │
│ volatile.                                                    │
│         if (!CB->onlyReadsMemory() || CB->isVolatile())      │
│           return false;                                      │
│ // ...                                                       │
│ ```                                                          │
│                                                              │
│ This change adds a check within `SimpleValue::isIdenticalTo` │
│ to ensure that two `CallBase` instructions are only          │
│ considered identical if they have the same `strictfp`        │
│ status. This prevents `early-cse` from attempting to CSE two │
│ calls with incompatible floating-point semantics, thus       │
│ avoiding the assertion failure.                              │
│                                                              │
│ <tool_code>                                                  │
