  "reason_thou": "### 1. Understanding the Issue\n\nThe
`early-cse` pass is asserting in `combineIRFlags` when
processing a function with two calls to the commutative
intrinsic `@llvm.smin.i32`. The two calls have swapped
arguments. One call site has the `strictfp` attribute, while the
other does not. The pass correctly identifies the two calls as
computationally equivalent due to the intrinsic's commutativity.
However, it fails when attempting to merge the attributes of the
two call sites because the `strictfp` attribute cannot be
intersected successfully when it's present on one call but not
the other.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe `opt` debug
log clearly shows that `early-cse` is attempting to common
subexpression eliminate (CSE) `%call2` with
`%call`:\n\n```\nEarlyCSE CSE:   %call2 = call i32
@llvm.smin.i32(i32 %arg1, i32 %arg)  to:   %call = call i32
@llvm.smin.i32(i32 %arg, i32 %arg1) #1\n```\n\n`%call` has
attribute `#1`, which is `{ strictfp }`, while `%call2` has no
attributes. The assertion failure happens in `combineIRFlags`,
which is called immediately before replacing `%call2` with
`%call`. The assertion message `Failed to intersect attributes
in callsites that passed identical check` confirms that the
`tryIntersectAttributes` function returned `false`, indicating a
failure to merge the attributes of the two call sites.\n\n### 3.
Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe root cause is a discrepancy between
the logic used to determine if two instructions are
\"identical\" and the logic used to merge their
attributes.\n\n1.  **Equality Check**: `early-cse` uses a helper
class `SimpleValue` and its `isIdenticalTo` method to check if
two instructions are candidates for CSE. For commutative
instructions like `@llvm.smin.i32`, this function canonicalizes
the operand order before comparison. This is why it correctly
identifies `%call` and `%call2` as computationally equivalent.
However, this equality check is incomplete as it *does not* take
into account certain call site attributes, such as
`strictfp`.\n\n2.  **Attribute Merging**: After `isIdenticalTo`
returns `true`, the pass proceeds to replace one instruction
with the other. As part of this process, it calls
`combineIRFlags` to merge the attributes of the two call sites.
This function calls `CallBase::tryIntersectAttributes`. The
intersection logic for an `EnumAttribute` like `strictfp`
requires that if the attribute is present on one call, it must
be present on the other for the intersection to succeed. \n\n3.
**The Conflict**: Since `%call` has `strictfp` and `%call2` does
not, `tryIntersectAttributes` fails. This failure triggers the
assertion because the pass made an incorrect assumption: that
any two instructions deemed \"identical\" by `isIdenticalTo`
would have mergeable attributes. The fundamental problem is that
the definition of \"identical\" was not strict enough.\n\n### 4.
Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe correct fix is to make the
equality check in `early-cse` aware of call site attributes that
cannot be safely merged if they differ. Specifically,
`SimpleValue::isIdenticalTo` should be modified to check for
incompatible `strictfp` attributes when comparing `CallBase`
instructions.\n\n**File**:
`llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/EarlyCSE.cpp`\n\n**Edit Point**: The
following code should be inserted at line 1010, inside the
`SimpleValue::isIdenticalTo` method.\n\n```cpp\n        // If
the calls have different strictfp attributes, they are not
identical.\n        if (CB->isStrictFP() !=
OtherCB->isStrictFP())\n          return false;\n```\n\nThis
change ensures that two calls are only considered identical for
CSE if their `strictfp` status matches, preventing the pass from
attempting to merge incompatible call sites and thus avoiding
the assertion.\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nBy strengthening the
equality check in `SimpleValue::isIdenticalTo` to include the
`strictfp` attribute, we resolve the inconsistency between the
instruction comparison logic and the attribute merging logic.
This fixes the immediate assertion failure and makes the
`early-cse` pass more robust by correctly handling an important
aspect of call site semantics.",
